WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.980
Let's keep going from the situation
objections into the trust objections.

2
00:00:05.500 --> 00:00:10.060
This is where sellers are asking whether they
can believe you, whether the people around

3
00:00:10.060 --> 00:00:13.700
them agree, and whether the problem in the
house is too big.

4
00:00:14.960 --> 00:00:18.020
When someone asks, are you going to flip
this for a profit?

5
00:00:18.040 --> 00:00:21.360
They're really asking whether they're
getting taken advantage of.

6
00:00:21.700 --> 00:00:24.340
Be honest. Yes, we're a business.

7
00:00:24.760 --> 00:00:28.180
We buy properties, improve them, and resell
them.

8
00:00:28.180 --> 00:00:34.080
That's how we're able to offer a fast cash
sale with no repairs and no commissions on

9
00:00:34.080 --> 00:00:36.860
their end. Don't apologize for the business
model.

10
00:00:37.240 --> 00:00:38.500
Just frame it honestly.

11
00:00:39.180 --> 00:00:41.440
Both sides get something they want.

12
00:00:42.720 --> 00:00:47.640
Scam concerns come up a lot, especially with
sellers who have been burned before.

13
00:00:48.200 --> 00:00:53.780
If someone says, I've been scammed, or is
this even legitimate, do not get defensive.

14
00:00:54.277 --> 00:00:56.182
Say you're sorry they went through that.

15
00:00:56.460 --> 00:01:00.040
Explain that everything goes through a
licensed title company.

16
00:01:00.040 --> 00:01:02.060
There's attorney review available.

17
00:01:02.520 --> 00:01:04.380
We never ask for money up front.

18
00:01:04.760 --> 00:01:09.700
They never pay us anything and offer to
share company information so they can verify

19
00:01:09.700 --> 00:01:11.660
everything before moving forward.

20
00:01:12.600 --> 00:01:17.200
When a seller says their attorney told them
not to sign anything, welcome that.

21
00:01:17.504 --> 00:01:18.695
Never fight the attorney.

22
00:01:18.794 --> 00:01:22.985
Say, that's great advice, and I'd encourage
you to have your attorney review everything.

23
00:01:23.060 --> 00:01:24.820
We work with attorneys regularly.

24
00:01:24.820 --> 00:01:29.400
If they have questions about our process or
the contract, we're happy to connect with

25
00:01:29.400 --> 00:01:34.280
them directly. Making the attorney your ally
instead of your opponent is one of the

26
00:01:34.280 --> 00:01:35.920
smartest things you can do.

27
00:01:36.960 --> 00:01:39.060
Family dynamics show up constantly.

28
00:01:39.460 --> 00:01:42.320
I want to sell, but my brother doesn't
agree.

29
00:01:42.860 --> 00:01:46.100
Or, my co-owner doesn't want to do this.

30
00:01:46.358 --> 00:01:50.820
These are tricky because you're dealing with
multiple people who have different priorities.

32
00:01:50.820 --> 00:01:54.380
Ask what the other person's main concern is.

33
00:01:54.760 --> 00:02:00.660
A lot of times, once they understand the full
picture, the costs of continuing to hold

34
00:02:00.660 --> 00:02:06.260
the property, the market conditions, what
their actual options are, they come around,

35
00:02:06.500 --> 00:02:08.620
offer to talk to the other party directly.

36
00:02:08.620 --> 00:02:13.780
Sometimes hearing it from an outside person
helps more than hearing it from family.

37
00:02:15.520 --> 00:02:19.060
Property issues. Sellers worry about
disclosing problems.

38
00:02:19.720 --> 00:02:21.800
Code violations. Asbestos.

39
00:02:22.460 --> 00:02:24.100
Mold. Foundation issues.

40
00:02:24.209 --> 00:02:26.543
All the stuff in the house they've been
ignoring.

41
00:02:26.543 --> 00:02:29.123
For all of these, the answer is the same.

42
00:02:29.420 --> 00:02:31.180
We buy properties in any condition.

43
00:02:31.740 --> 00:02:33.500
That's literally what we do.

44
00:02:33.920 --> 00:02:37.240
Whatever the issue is, it doesn't change our
interest.

45
00:02:37.480 --> 00:02:40.080
We just factor it into the evaluation.

46
00:02:41.040 --> 00:02:45.540
For personal belongings, tell them they can
take whatever they want.

47
00:02:46.160 --> 00:02:48.540
Anything they leave behind, we handle.

48
00:02:48.920 --> 00:02:53.500
A lot of sellers, especially elderly ones
and people dealing with inherited properties,

49
00:02:53.920 --> 00:02:57.700
find huge relief in hearing that they don't
have to clean the whole place out

50
00:02:57.700 --> 00:02:58.500
themselves.

51
00:02:59.040 --> 00:03:03.980
The pattern across every one of these is the
same framework you already know.

52
00:03:04.580 --> 00:03:06.100
Listen to the concern fully.

53
00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:08.700
Acknowledge it so they know you heard them.

54
00:03:09.100 --> 00:03:11.880
Ask questions to get to the real issue
underneath.

55
00:03:12.260 --> 00:03:15.160
And redirect toward a solution or a next
step.

56
00:03:15.160 --> 00:03:19.380
The specific words change depending on the
situation.

57
00:03:19.980 --> 00:03:21.760
The framework doesn't.

58
00:03:23.100 --> 00:03:26.000
One thing worth saying about these advanced
situations.

59
00:03:26.740 --> 00:03:29.080
They often carry heavy emotional weight.

60
00:03:29.720 --> 00:03:32.540
Grief. Embarrassment. Fear.

61
00:03:33.360 --> 00:03:34.160
Family conflict.

62
00:03:34.160 --> 00:03:38.500
The people who handle them best on the phone
aren't the ones with the smoothest

63
00:03:38.500 --> 00:03:43.040
rebuttals. They're the ones who genuinely
care about the person on the other end of the

64
00:03:43.040 --> 00:03:44.720
line. You can't fake that.

65
00:03:45.080 --> 00:03:46.000
Sellers can tell.

66
00:03:47.320 --> 00:03:52.140
Your roleplay for this section is a cold
outreach to someone in pre-foreclosure who

67
00:03:52.140 --> 00:03:53.740
thinks you're running a scam.

68
00:03:54.220 --> 00:03:55.580
It's as real as it gets.

69
00:03:56.580 --> 00:03:59.780
Once you've run it, one more stop in this
section.

70
00:04:00.440 --> 00:04:04.900
The questions sellers ask that aren't objections
at all and how to answer them without

71
00:04:04.900 --> 00:04:05.700
flinching.
